  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concern—it's a real, tangible barrier that affects how people approach learning and innovation. Having grown up in Rome with parents who had limited formal education, I've always been acutely aware of how expectations can shape outcomes. When I was younger, I remember sitting in school with classmates who seemed to know more than me about math and science, even though I was just as eager to learn. The fear of being labeled 'not good at it' or 'not smart enough' could make someone freeze in front of a problem, especially if they belonged to a group that was historically underrepresented in these fields. This isn't about individual failure; it's about systemic pressures that create a self-fulfilling prophecy. For instance, a young woman in my neighborhood might hesitate to join a coding club because she's worried her peers will think she's 'not cut out for it.' Addressing this requires more than just awareness—it needs practical, community-driven solutions. I've seen how simple changes, like mentorship programs that pair students with role models who look like them, or inclusive teaching methods that validate diverse learning styles, can make a real difference. In my own life, I've tried to foster this mindset by encouraging my children to explore STEM through hands-on projects, like building robots or coding games, without letting fear of judgment overshadow their curiosity. The key is to create environments where everyone feels safe to fail and to grow. Ultimately, we must shift from seeing STEM as a single path to success to recognizing it as a space where all backgrounds and experiences can contribute meaningfully. This isn't just about fixing the problem—it's about building a future where everyone has the chance to thrive.",
